Exploratory analysis: Substantive limits

This exploratory analysis focuses on the Substantive limits dimension and includes various data summaries in table and graphical forms.

Aims

The Substantive Limits is an important dimension for LIDD, and one where we have got some good measures. Ill go through a simple thought experiment to highlight what we need to do. Basically, its all about applying domain knowledge to the case at hand.

Lets assume that there is a true model of the Substantive Limits out there and it is composed of 4 equally important categories of prohibitions, A, B, C and D. Lets further assume that A, B, C and D can be measured with 5 items each (20 items altogether).

Now assume we correctly identify the four categories A, B, C and D. And we measure category A with 14 items, and the rest with only 2 items per category. Finally, we estimate a countrys score by adding up all the Yes scores to the 20 items and dividing by 20.

Our final measure would problably be problematic, it would give excess weight to category A and imperfectly measure the other categories. One solution could be to measure the 4 categories separately, and then add them up -this would give equal weight to all 4 categories.

In the real world there is no true model (or one that we could ever know in the sense above), the best we can do is to approximate it based on domain knowledge (theory) and good data and measurement. The illustration above gives an idea of the task at hand, which evidently applies to all Dimensions we are tyrying to measure.

In our case, we started off with a set of prohibitions based on domain knowldege. Now that we have some data back we can update our earlier intuitions to create a measure that somehow approximates the Dimension were interested in.

The Substantive Limits scale has been constructed on the basis of these items:

65 Are referendums on issues related to local governance prohibited?
66 Are there any other prohibited issues?

Note 1: for the Law-initiated, Item 47 was not available.

Note 2: Item 46 is like a filter, if No then score is 0.

Note 3: Item 66 -on Other prohibitions- is not analysed.

Data Summaries

To get an idea of the distribution of the items we have used to meausre Substantive Limits well begin with some visualistations of the data.

In all cases below, we have removed Item 46 (on general prohibitions) and Item 66 (on Other prohibitions). Furthermore we have excluded all cases where the answer to Item 46 is No. This means the analysis below is ONLY of cases that have substantive prohibition(s). This is important and will enable us to see how the prohibitions are clustered among countries that have them.

The graph below looks at all the items (47:65) and counts the number of cases with prohibitions. It does so without distinguishing among the different Instruments. The Blue area represents all the No while yellow blocks are the Yes values.

Number of Yes/No per item (all Instruments combined)

The take home point in the graph above is that some items have very few cases, especially those items on the left side of the red dashed line. Thus, items 51, 58, 60 and 63 all have three or less Yes values.

The next graph does the same thing but further disaggregates by Instrument. In this case, the dahsed red line is set at 2 cases.

Number of Yes/No per item grouped by Instrument

In this graph its possible to see that for instance Law-initiated has more totally blue areas -indicating all No, which is unsurprising given the nature of the Instrument.

Country check

Another aspect worth checking is the Country impact. The visualisation below allows us to check how Country affects substantive prohibitions. It is organised by the items on Y axis and the Countries on the X axis. The bubble represent the count (i.e., how many prohibitions a country has per item). This is related to the number of instruments a country has; thus a country with 5, will have a maximum number of 5 prohibitions.

Visualising these country effects allows us to see whether a particular country is driving the Yes count for a particular Item.

Matrix of Yes value count for each item organised by country

In the graph we can look at distributions by Item by focusing on horizontal axis (left-to-right) of a specific item. For instance we can see that Items 54 and 56 have lots of bubbles, indicating lots of Yes answers.

Note that empty spaces (i.e.no bubbles) indicate no cases. Thus for item 58 we can only see one small bubble, in this case its a prohibition in Denmark.

But the graph can also tell us about country effects -which is measured by the size of the bubble. We now need to read the graph vertically (bottom-to-top). Doing so reveals that, for instance, Russia is driving the count related to item 65 while Turkey is doing the same for item 51. Item 59 also has very instances. These replication effects occur because a countrys prohibitions will be repeated across Instruments.

Summary

A quick overview would suggest that some items might be problematic. The following all have 3 or less count:

  • Item 58 = Naturalisation
  • Item 51 = State symbols
  • Item 63 = Executive competencies
  • Item 60 = Election/Referendum rules

While Country replication effects indicate possible issues with items 65, 59 and 52.

Annex

Preliminary evaluation of scores

In the graph below we can place all cases on a putative Substantive Limits dimension. Because of the way the dimension has been measured, it has lots of items that are sparsely populated there is little variation across the Instruments. In other words, it is virtually impossible to get a high score because we have so many items. So, some sort of grouping and removal of sparse items is probably in order.
